The grammar is extremely “permissive’’:  

1. Every terminal symbol occurring in the string is produced directly by at least one non-terminal of the grammar.  
2. Those non-terminals in turn appear in many binary rules, so they can be combined with one another.  
3. The start symbol S can reach non-terminals that (by recursive use of the rules) are able to concatenate arbitrary sequences of such terminals.  
   • For instance, S → NT5 NT8, and both NT5 and NT8 can lengthen their yields indefinitely by rules such as  
     NT5 → NT1 NT5, NT5 → NT2 NT0, NT8 → NT0 NT8, NT8 → NT8 NT11, …  
   • Because every terminal of the target string can be introduced somewhere inside NT5 or NT8, the whole 30-token sequence can be split between the left and right halves of S and then produced inductively.

Since no symbol in the given string is outside the terminal alphabet of the grammar and there is no structural restriction preventing the needed concatenations, the grammar can indeed derive the entire string.

Yes
